See Juv. xiv. 153. “Tunicam mihi malo lupini,'' &cu ‘ Farratam ollam ’ is a jar of porridge, ‘puls.’ See Juv. xi. 109, where ‘farrata' is used absolutely for ‘pultes' See also his description of the young rustics’ supper, “grandes fumabant pul- tibus ollae’' (xiv. 171). The slaves clapped their hands when they saw this mess, It was an improvement on their ordinary meals: but what could they have been? for ‘far' was the daily allowance of slaves in general.
